Scientific Explanation (Plain English)
Gravitational lensing occurs when massive objects (like galaxy clusters) bend the path of light coming from objects behind them, acting like a giant cosmic lens. According to General Relativity, the amount of bending depends on the total mass along the line of sight.
In many galaxy clusters, the amount of bending observed is much greater than what can be accounted for by the visible stars, gas, and dust. This “missing mass” is what mainstream physics attributes to dark matter.
The post uses this as visual evidence that dark matter must exist.
